In TypeScript, you can use the "as" operator to indicate that you know that a value will only have one of a set of types. The "as" operator is similar to the "typeof" operator in JavaScript, except it allows you to explicitly state which type you expect the value to have, rather than only being able to detect it at runtime.

Here's an example:
```typescript
var obj = {
    name: "John",
};

// Get a property on obj.name. If it is a string, return it. If it is an object, return undefined.
var val = obj.name as string;
```
In this example, we first declare a variable named obj that has a property named "name". We then use the as operator to specify that we expect the value of this property to be either a string or undefined, depending on whether it is a string or an object. We then use the val variable to access this property and return the value of the property as a string if it is a string, and undefined if it is an object.

